Content-Based Recommendation Systems¶

The first system we look at is a Content-Based Filtering System. For this purpose, we use this dataset (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/harshitshankhdhar/imdb-dataset-of-top-1000-movies-and-tv-shows) that contains data on the top 1000 movies based on IMDB ratings. We use the description of the movie as well as the name of the director, the genre and the most prominent actors in the movie as a basis for the system. Building the recommendation system relies on a few steps:

  1. Natural Language Processing: We combine the text data from the different features (overview, director, etc.) into a text. Note that you can apply different weights based on the importance that the features have for you in the system. The resulting texts undergoes some natural language processing (lemmatization and TFIDF-vectorization) as it is translated into numerical features.
  2. Similarity measures: The resulting numerical features of the input data is compared to the similarly processed data of the remaining movies. The comparison can be based on different measures. For this project, we used so called cosine similarity. There is an explanation of this metric below. Other possible metrics are the Euclidean distance or the Manhattan distance.
  3. Selection: Based on the similarity measure, the five movies that are most closely related to the input movies are selected.

We note here that this system has a clear weakness: If you like a movie from a franchise, recommendations are very likely to come from the same franchise. In general, there is a very limited set of movies to generate the recommendations. This is a consideration for future work on a larger dataset.

This notebook can be found on Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/code/alinagdartmouth/movierecommendation-contentbased

Data preprocessing¶

Missing values¶

From the information, we note that neither the runtime nor the year of release are integers (but strings instead). So, the first step is to transform the data to integer values for easier handling. There is also one release year missing. We fill the year by looking up the one movie. Since there are more entries missing for the Certificate, the Meta-Score and the Gross, this approach is not feasible here. Instead, we fill the numerical values (Meta-Score and Gross) with the mean of the other movies and the Certificate with a new category: Missing. Further, we drop the link to the poster.

Some illustrations¶

After looking at the genres, we generate illustrations for the remaining data columns. We will go through each of the seven plots in order.

  1. Release year: It becomes clear that there are significantly more newer movies. This might be related to the increasing number of movies released each year as well as to the changing expectations of movie goers. We note here that this dataset is very restricted in that we are only considering movies with high ratings. This makes it hard to distinguish which factor is more important here.
  2. Certificate: A surprising amount of movies are R rated/A rated. This suggests that while these movies typically generate smaller box office, they can generate high ratings.
  3. Runtime: The runtime almost follows a normal distribution with a tilt towards longer movies.
  4. IMDB Rating: The ratings have been cut off at roughly 7.5, due to the nature of the dataset.
  5. Meta-Score: Unlike the IMDB ratings (from the public), the Meta-Score generated based on critics' opinions have not been cut off. They are almost normally distributed.
  6. No of votes: The number of votes is roughly exponentially distributed (as one might expect).
  7. Gross: The box office is roughly exponentially distributed (as one might expect).

Correlations¶

The next step was to generate a correlation heat map. Some very interesting observations by strength of correlation:

  1. No of votes and box office are positively correlated. This makes sense as more popular movies get more votes.
  2. No of votes and IMDB score are positively correlated. If a movie has a high IMDB score more people are interested in watching the movie.
  3. Older movies have a higher meta score and slightly higher IMDB score. This might be due to a certain selection bias against older movies which makes only 'good' movies become 'classics' with high critical acclaim.
  4. Higher IMDB rating means higher meta score. The opinion of the public and of critics has a relatively high correlation.
  5. Newer films have higher box office and more votes.
  6. Longer runtime gives higher IMDB rating. This might be due to (7.)
  7. Newer films are longer.
  8. Longer runtime means more votes and higher box office. This is probably due to (7.)

from string import punctuation
from collections import Counter

# Download NLTK stopwords (if not already downloaded)
nltk.download('stopwords')

# Assuming df_movies is your DataFrame

# Concatenate all 'Overview' texts into a single string
all_overviews = ' '.join(df_movies['Overview'].dropna())

# Tokenize the text into words
words = word_tokenize(all_overviews)

# Filter out stopwords, common punctuation marks, and 's'
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
filtered_words = [word.lower() for word in words if word.lower() not in stop_words and word.lower() not in punctuation and word.lower() != "'s"]

# Count the frequency of each word
word_freq = Counter(filtered_words)

# Get the most common words and their frequencies
top_words = word_freq.most_common(10)  # Change the number as needed

# Plotting the bar plot

Recommendation System¶

To actually build a recommendation system, for each movie, we build a vector that consists of the content (i.e. overview), the director, the genre and the actors. For each of the features, we can choose a weight, i.e. the importance of the factor for the recommendation system. So, each movie ends up with a vector that represents its content-based features. To get movies similar to the movies we choose, we build a vector for the combination of the movies. Finally, we find other movies with vectors pointing in a similar direction (i.e. we are looking for vectors with large cosine similarity). This means that our recommendation system takes the features of the movies and translates them into a single numerical feature that is easily comparable. An demonstration of the system can be found here: (include link)

In [50]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity

# Assuming 'Overview', 'Director', and 'Star' are features
features = ['Overview', 'Director', 'Genre','Star1','Star2','Star3','Star4']

# Define weights for each feature
weights = {'Overview': 1, 'Director': 0.3, 'Genre': 0.3,'Star1':0.05,'Star2':0.05,'Star3':0.05,'Star4':0.05}

# Fill NaN values with an empty string
df_movies[features] = df_movies[features].fillna('')

# Combine text features into a single column
df_movies['Combined_Text'] = df_movies[features].apply(lambda row: ' '.join(row), axis=1)

# Fit the TfidfVectorizer to the combined text
tfidf_vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()
combined_tfidf_matrix = tfidf_vectorizer.fit_transform(df_movies['Combined_Text'])

# Function to transform individual features based on the fitted vectorizer and apply weights
def transform_feature(feature):
    feature_tfidf_matrix = tfidf_vectorizer.transform(df_movies[feature])
    return feature_tfidf_matrix * weights[feature]

# Transform individual features
tfidf_matrices = {feature: transform_feature(feature) for feature in features}

# Combine individual feature matrices
combined_tfidf_matrix = sum(tfidf_matrices.values())

# Calculate cosine similarity
cosine_sim = cosine_similarity(combined_tfidf_matrix, combined_tfidf_matrix)

# Function for movie recommendations
def get_recommendations(input_movies):
    input_indices = []
    for movie_title in input_movies:
        idx = df_movies[df_movies['Series_Title'] == movie_title].index
        if not idx.empty:
            input_indices.append(idx[0])

    if not input_indices:
        return "No matches found for input movies."

    sim_scores = cosine_sim[input_indices].sum(axis=0)

    # Exclude input movies from recommendations
    exclude_indices = np.array(input_indices)
    sim_scores[exclude_indices] = -1

    # Get top recommendations
    movie_indices = sim_scores.argsort()[::-1][:5]
    return df_movies['Series_Title'].iloc[movie_indices]

# Example usage
input_movies = ['The Matrix', 'Dunkirk', 'The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring']
recommendations = get_recommendations(input_movies)
print(recommendations)

Future Directions¶

While this system can already find similar movies, it does not take into account many movies due to the size of the data set. Future work should take into account a larger dataset. Additionally, we currently have recommendation systems that are either based solely on content-based or collaborative filtering. In the future, I plan to use a larger dataset with both content-based and collaborative data to build a hybrid recommendation system.
